<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Economic Diary: Other economic news
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Wednesday: The initial estimate of US GDP growth in the third quarter is
expected to be revised upwards, from 3.4 per cent to 3.5 per cent. A more
substantial upward revision would spark speculation about further interest
rate increases from the Federal Reserve.
Thursday: The purchasing managers' index is one of the month's earliest
economic indicators in both the UK and the US. The UK version should give a
further guide to the price pressures on the corporate sector; the Bank of
England has expressed concern that output price inflation might be passed
through to the High Street. Prices are also a concern in the US; in October,
the index's prices component was at its highest level since June 1988.
Friday: The increase in non-farm payroll employment has been one of the most
closely-watched US indicators. Last month, the figure which provoked
inflationary concern was a jump in average hourly earnings. A fall in the
unemployment rate from October's 5.8 per cent would also be seen as a sign
of future price pressures. UK official reserves are expected to have edged
up by Dollars 25m in November.
</TEXT>
