<DATE>941128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / World Bond Markets: Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The German bond market put on a show of strength last week after the more
favourable inflation figures and lower than expected money supply growth.
But some economists reckon this upturn was misplaced.
'We can detect precious little in the recent data that could serve as a
justification of the bond market rally these last days,' said Mr Adolf
Rosenstock at the Industrial Bank of Japan's Frankfurt office.
'We interpret it instead as a spill-over from the rally in the US bond
market, which we consider a bear market still.'
It came as no surprise that the Bundesbank left interest rates unchanged on
Thursday. The bank is waiting for a more marked slowdown in M3 growth and
inflation and stronger evidence of wage moderation before deciding whether
to opt for a final discount and Lombard rate cut in the present economic
cycle.
'The Bundesbank could have some reason to cut rates,' reckons Mr Norbert
Braem of Barclays de Zoete Wedd. Key interest rates have not reached the
lows seen in previous cycles.
'The Bundesbank will be ready to support the economy to some extent,' he
added. There is no reason for this now, he says, but there could be in 1995
if economic recovery stalls because of increased D-Mark strength or sluggish
private consumption.
</TEXT>
