<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / International Company News: Higher costs restrict ITC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOMBAY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Launch expenses of low-cost cigarette brands and an oilseeds business
decline restricted sales and profit growth of India's biggest tobacco
company, ITC, Reuter reports from Bombay.
ITC reported an 11 per cent increase in gross sales to Rs22.77bn (Dollars
726m) and a 30 per cent rise in net profit to Rs1.16bn for the half year to
September 30 but the earnings increase was modest compared with the general
trend of many companies posting more than 100 per cent rises for the half
year, analysts said.
'It is a little disappointing for a market which is used to better results
from ITC,' said one. 'They focused on high volume sales of low cost brands
in rural India. This is a good strategy in the long run, but marketing
expenses eroded margins.'
ITC, which is 31.5 per cent owned by BAT Industries of the UK, recorded a
6.4 per cent increase in cigarette sales in value terms after several years
of stagnant growth. Cigarettes contribute to more than 60 per cent of ITC's
sales.
</TEXT>
