<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Not the cheeriest way to round off Monday, but The New Middle Ages (11.15pm,
BBC 2) is totally riveting. Expert predictions of new plagues, mysticism and
millennial panic are all the more impressive for lack of portentousness or
hysteria. Old enemies return in newly medicinally resistant shape 'almost in
cataclysmic proportions'. New killers emerge, including Ebola, a 'level four
monster' according to American Richard Preston (Aids is only level two),
which needs a biological space-suit to handle and could, if released, assume
Black Death dimensions. Professor Norman Stone evokes the Wars of the Roses
and 'robber barons' to describe our new tribalism.
Yet, as the medieval mind held to religious certainties, so today scientists
fitfully discern a pattern in nature, a 'mysterious organising principle'.
And the fanatic, unctuous gleam of a member of the architectural profession
certainly recalls the privileged medieval church: unaccountable, disdainful
of the populace, and inflicting misery in the name of its own superior
wisdom.
</TEXT>
