<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV Editor, Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An astonishing 2 per cent of Americans - that is three times the population
of Birmingham - claim to have been abducted by aliens, and they can't all be
mad. Psychologist Susan Blackmore investigates them for Horizon (Monday
8.00-8.50pm, BBC2) and finds enough similarity between their accounts of
being taken away by little grey men to intrigue her - and us. Is it a
variation of false memory syndrome, or is there a more obvious physical
cause? The programme takes the matter seriously and thus raises a few
unintentional laughs, but remains completely absorbing.
Channel Tunnel investors may well be chuckling tonight as Panorama
(9.30-10.10pm, BBC1) asks if there is an inherrent flaw in roll-on, roll-off
ferries. When The Estonia went down in the Baltic sea, it was the second
major disaster involving such vessels in seven years. In both cases large
numbers of lives were lost. Are warnings being ignored? Is cost a more
pressing consideration than safety at sea?
Matthew Parris sets out to puncture PR puffery. In Bad Ideas Of the
Twentieth Century (Tuesday 9.00-9.45, C4), the former MP argues that whether
directed towards good or bad ends, PR always ends up sullying the
individuals concerned.
High Interest (Sunday 5.10-6.00pm C4) lives up to its title with a frank
profile of George Soros, the financier whose dealings contributed to
Britain's exit from the ERM. Soros has annual earnings as high as
Sainsbury's profits, but gives half of them to charity, not all of which is
gratefully received. He talks about his strategy, his losses and his
do-gooding with disarming honesty.
Kruschev was as subtle a strategist as the Red Queen and her impulsive
beheadings. Timewatch (Sunday, 9.00-10.00pm, BBC2) reveals how he would take
a revolver with him to meetings in case argument didn't work. The man was so
feared that Brezhnev, after giving orders to have him killed, lost his nerve
and sobbed. This fascinating profile, which traces Krushchev's rise from
peasent to potentate, has some extraordinary stories, including the blackly
comic one of how Stalin's body was removed from its place next to Lenin's in
the dead of night.
</TEXT>
