<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / This Week: FT Guide to Boss of the Year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain is holding its breath this week: not so much for tonight's
confidence vote at Westminster, or tomorrow's Budget, but for the result on
Wednesday of the Boss of the Year award. What is the origin of 'boss'?
Dictionaries say it is derived from the Dutch word baas, meaning master or
uncle, and is probably related to the old High German basa (aunt). The word
can have slighly perjorative connotations - when used, for example, in
relation to politicians who control a party machine - though the
once-sinister BOSS (South African Bureau of State Security) is an acronym
and strictly no relation. In Australia, boss-cocky is an informal term for
especially overbearing bosses. Companies called Boss have had mixed
fortunes. The German menswear business Hugo Boss - which has a Boss men's
fragrance - has been making a good contribution to the profits of its
Italian parent, Marzotto. The British fork-lift truck manufacturer Lancer
Boss, however, went into receivership earlier this year and is now owned by
the German company Jungheinrich.
Is there a typical boss?
A typical UK director is a 52-year-old male, though the age range is late
teens to early 90s. Women are outnumbered 35:1 in British boardrooms. Until
he stepped down earlier this year as non-executive deputy chairman of the
south coast motor group Caffyns, the oldest incumbent of a publicly quoted
company was thought to be 92-year-old Lord Shawcross.
How many other bosses can you boss?
Professor Sir Roland Smith, former chairman of British Aerospace, used to be
the record holder with 11 non-executive directorships (he now has a mere
six). At the last count, George Duncan led the field with eight.
Who is the toughest boss?
Lord Sheppard, chairman of Grand Metropolitan, holds this distinction in
Britain, according to one poll, though he was once reputedly so mild on a
visit to an American subsidiary that his hosts thought they had the wrong
man. Certainly he sounds tame by comparison with T J Rodgers, ceo of
California-based Cypress Semiconductors and America's toughest boss in 1993,
according to Fortune. Rodgers routinely reduces employees to tears, and has
developed what is known inside the company as 'killer software' - that
tracks down and penalises employees by stopping their cheques. He told one:
'I am willing to see your children's tuition payments go away and for you to
lose your house and go on welfare ..'
Who is the meanest boss?
Earlier this year the FT made a valiant attempt to unearth this unworthy
individual, but the 'competition' was quickly abandoned in the absence of
suitable nominations. It is no doubt prejudicial to say so, but perhaps the
media ogre Robert Maxwell should have had the honour conferred posthumously
(to be held in perpetuity).
Who is the highest paid boss?
Michael Eisner of Disney, with Dollars 203m, topped a Business Week survey
last April measuring all remuneration (including stock options). Lou
Gerstner's Dollars 7.7m of salary, bonus and other payments heads a
Wyatt/Fortune list published in July. Peter Wood, chief executive of the
Royal Bank of Scotland's insurance subsidiary Direct Line, wins the UK's
biggest prize - a Pounds 21m 'contract variation' this year plus a Pounds
350,000 salary. According to Labour Research, an independent consultancy, 71
UK directors received more than Pounds 100m between them in share dividends
last year (among them, payouts to Sir Andrew Lloyd Webber of Really Useful
Holdings of Pounds 13.3m and to David Sainsbury of grocer J Sainsbury of
Pounds 11m).
Which car do bosses typically like to drive?
A poll conducted by Reward and the Institute of Directors puts the Jaguar
way ahead, even though its popularity fell from 84 per cent to 79 per cent
last year. Mercedes was second.
Why is there a Boss of the Year award?
Largely, one suspects, to generate publicity on local radio and in local
newspapers for the international distribution company sponsoring the event.
This year's finalists include 35-year-old Henry Stewart, boss of the
London-based IT training company Happy Computers, who personally inspired a
4pm ice-cream break for clients and staff, allows staff to choose their own
titles and job descriptions, and arranged for a bouncy castle to be hired
for a recent agm. The current Boss of the Year is Reg Key of Chubb Fire.
</TEXT>
