<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Auditors oppose disclosure of 'letter'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Company auditors and managers believe that publication of the 'management
letter' would improve corporate governance - yet most auditors do not want
to disclose the contents of the letter, says a survey published today.
The 'management letter' allows auditors to advise management on accounting
methods, internal controls and ways to improve efficiency. It is never
disclosed to shareholders, in spite of their technical role in being
ultimately responsible for the appointment of the auditor.
The survey, by the department of accounting and financial management at the
University of Essex, was based on interviews with 105 top auditors and 181
managers at the top 100 listed companies.
Auditors, asked to score the benefits of publication between one for 'none',
and five for 'great extent' gave an average figure of 3.12 in terms of
improving shareholders' assessment of management competence. However, 63 per
cent of auditors rejected suggestions that they should formally report on
company procedures in their audit report.
Professor Michael Sherer of the University of Essex said: 'It is somewhat
ironic that whilst auditors are appointed by shareholders to monitor the
activities of management, shareholders have little means of evaluating how
effectively auditors are performing their monitoring task.'
Mr Gerry Acher, head of audit at accountants KPMG Peat Marwick, said
although he had not studied the research he felt management letters were of
little use to shareholders. He said: 'It would be like buying a car and
being given a technical assessment of the fuel-burning qualities of the
vehicle.'
The Usefulness of Management Letters. ACCA, PO Box 66, Glasgow, G41 1BS.
Pounds 9.95.
</TEXT>
