<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Radical agenda urged on Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A call for the government to abandon consolidation in favour of a radical
agenda of reform was issued yesterday by a prominent rightwinger on the Tory
back benches.
Mr Edward Leigh, the former technology minister identified as a key figure
behind efforts to promote a leadership challenge to Mr John Major, warned
that a 'steady as she goes' policy risked becoming 'steady as she sinks'.
Mr Leigh, a strong critic of the decision to drop privatisation of the Post
Office, said the government had to weave the traditional threads of Tory
philosophy into a populist and radical programme for the next century.
He said in a pamphlet published by the Conservative Political Centre that
the platform should be based on the notion of 'responsible individualism'.
That meant empowering individuals through the market economy while equally
supporting the creation of an 'ethical' society through leadership and
legislation.
Alongside traditional Tory commitments to strong defence, law and order, and
firm support of British sovereignty in Europe, the pamphlet suggests a range
of new policies.
He also calls for the present leadership rules to be replaced by a framework
which would ensure one contest during the lifetime of each parliament.
Meanwhile, Mr William Powell, Tory MP for Corby, last night called on Mr
Major to resign and stand for re-election, to end speculation about his
leadership.
He told BBC Radio Five Live that he did not want to see a leadership
challenge, but believed Mr Major could end the speculation and reimpose
party discipline by winning a leadership contest.
Responsible Individualism. CPC Bookshop, Conservative Central Office, 32
Smith Square, London SW1P 3HH. Pounds 4.
</TEXT>
