<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / MPs seek views of ministers' energy experts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A committee of MPs is seeking advice from a government-appointed panel of
experts on next year's flotation of the National Grid and other topical
energy matters.
The Commons trade and industry committee has asked for the views of the
government's Energy Advisory Panel on clean-coal technology, competitiveness
in the electricity generation and supply sectors, and the National Grid. It
has asked the panel to respond by the end of March.
The committee's move is novel because the panel was set up to advise
ministers.
The Department of Trade and Industry said last week that the question of
whether the panel could advise other people had never been raised. If it
was, it would be considered, the department said.
The National Grid, the power transmission company in England and Wales,
which is owned by the regional electricity companies, is expected to be
floated on the London Stock Exchange next summer. The flotation price could
be as high as Pounds 5bn. The committee has asked for the panel's views on
what consequences the flotation will have and how the proceeds should be
distributed.
The 16-member panel, which was announced in last year's coal white paper,
was set up to advise on the 'interpretation' of information in the
government's annual energy report and its implications for future market
developments.'
Members of the panel include executives from the energy sector,
conservationists, academics and representatives of trade union and consumer
interests.
The regional electricity companies are discussing flotation plans with the
government, which holds a golden share in the National Grid, and are likely
to announce details within the next few months.
The flotation is likely to take the form of a demerger whereby shareholders
in the regional companies would be given new shares in the Grid. The
companies are expected to load the Grid with debt of about Pounds 750m to
help pay a Pounds 1bn tax bill and consumer rebates of more than Pounds
200m.
</TEXT>
