<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Companies seen to tighten discipline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Employment Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many of Britain's companies have tightened disciplinary procedures for
employees and increased the range of disciplinary offences during the past
six years, according to a survey published today by the independent Labour
Research Department.
It found that 79 per cent of 147 procedure agreements covered in the survey
had been tightened or modified over the period. 'The range of possible
offences is increasing and cover a wide variety of issues not previously the
subject of discipline including smoking, sex and race harassment and
computer-related offences,' says the report.
The body suggested there was 'some evidence to suggest that companies have
used the recession and the lengthening unemployment queues to tighten up on
discipline'.
The proportion of workplaces considering sexual and racial harassment as
matters of gross misconduct by employees has risen from 3 per cent in 1988
to 16 per cent.
The survey found that 54 per cent of company procedure agreements provided
for a formal hearing before the imposition of any discipline. Employees had
the right to union representation in a disciplinary case in 77 per cent of
workplaces but in only 49 per cent did this provide for a formal hearing.
Only 3 per cent of workplaces allowed their employees to see their personal
files. As many as 98 per cent of agreements provided a right to appeal,
compared with 79 per cent in 1988.
While 61 per cent of workplaces gave employees at least three warnings
before dismissing them, one in three companies provided for the suspension
of an employee in a disciplinary case, with the average suspension being
five days.
The survey suggests employee representatives are experiencing difficulties
with procedures either because management want to amend them or because the
procedures may not be operated quite in the way they had been laid down.
Bargaining Report No 144. Labour Research Department, 78 Blackfriars Rd,
London SE1N 8HF. Pounds 2.95
</TEXT>
