<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Report on durability of consumer goods
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumer goods should be made to last longer rather than being sent for
recycling when they are no longer required, says a report by an economic
think-tank published today, Deborah Hargreaves writes.
The New Economics Foundation says longer-lasting products would be much more
beneficial to the environment than recycling, which the report's author
criticises as inadequate and a 'third-rate' option. Mr Tim Cooper, the
author, says more than 6m large kitchen appliances, 3m vacuum cleaners and
2m cars are discarded in Britain each year.
He criticises the current emphasis on recycling, noting that recycling
itself uses energy and adds to pollution.
Mr Cooper says that recycling is preferable to landfill, but should be
ranked third after waste reduction which involves building longer-lasting
products, and re-using products and their components.
The report claims that companies could gain a beneficial marketing edge by
producing more durable goods. It also advocates significantly longer
guarantees for products and a shift in taxes from labour to energy and raw
materials.
Beyond Recycling: The Longer Life Option. New Economics Foundation, Vine
Court, 112-116 Whitechapel Road, London E1 1JE. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
<XX>
