<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / NHS staff crisis feared as forecasts attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Health Service could face a shortage of nurses and occupational
therapists in the next few years because of flaws in the system for
predicting staffing needs.
A report by the Institute for Manpower Studies for the NHS executive says
regional health authorities in England have been forced to make 'heroic
assumptions' about future staffing needs for nursing and occupational
therapists in England. The report, which has not been published, says
workforce planners face 'lack of reliable data' in deciding on the
allocation of training places.
Since the 1991 NHS reforms the 14 English regional health authorities have
been responsible for identifying demand for newly qualified staff. The NHS
executive conducts an annual poll of each authority and develops a five-year
plan to make sure a national supply of trained staff is maintained.
But the report says the short-term nature of the service contracting process
with staff makes long-term forecasts difficult. In addition, it says, little
historical data about turnover of staff is available to the regional health
authorities.
The length of training programmes and the over-reliance on current
productivity levels also skews forecasts, it says. The report points out
that private-sector healthcare employers are often unwilling or unable to
contribute to the exercise and therefore training needs can be
underestimated.
The report says that workforce planning is not given a high priority. 'All
too often,' it says, planning appears to be 'delegated to junior staff in
personnel, who lack the authority to challenge staffing assumptions'.
The Department of Health said the executive was considering the
recommendations in the report, which also recommends options for improving
data collection and forecasting methods.
The Royal College of Nursing, the College of Occupational Therapists, and
Unison, the main health service union, say that regional determination of
training needs is flawed because it leaves gaps in forecasts. They believe
central determination of needs is required.
Mr Tom Bolger, RCN director of education, said the number of training places
for nurses had dropped 33 per cent since 1987. He said he had heard reports
that health authorities in London and the Thames region could not fill
nursing vacancies and that advertised jobs in nursing journals had doubled
in the past 12 months. He said: 'Unless something drastic is done to
increase the number of students then we are likely to have a crisis of
shortages in the future.'
Ms Georgina Smith, director of education at the College of Occupational
Therapists, said: 'I think there is going to be a training crisis as the
health service continues to be devolved.'
</TEXT>
