<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Budget 1994: Direct tax cuts find little favour - Chris
Tighe and Stuart Dalby discover few people expecting good news in tomorrow's
Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE, STUART DALBY, ALISON MAITLAND, ALAN CANE and CHARLES
BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chancellor may be heartened to learn that according to a cross-section
of people contacted by the Financial Times, the public does not expect much
good news in tomorrow's Budget.
Mr David Rist, marketing director of the British Shoe Corporation,
responsible for the Hush Puppy shoes Mr Kenneth Clarke wears, said consumers
remained cautious and were not spending.
He said: 'It would be nice if the chancellor could make a gesture which
would boost confidence. But I simply cannot see it. Tax cuts are simply not
on the agenda.'
Mr Paul Handley, finance director of Mansfield Brewery, the beer-drinking
chancellor's local brewer, said: 'We are constantly told the economy is
coming out of recession but the consumer has still got to come out of the
closet. People are still worried about their mortgages, their jobs.'
Our interviewees, whose reactions to the Budget we will report on Wednesday,
include chief executives, small businessmen, a farmer, a pensioner, a writer
and an unemployed man in Britain's worst unemployment blackspot.
Most disliked the idea of further cuts in direct taxation, if the price to
be paid was increases in indirect tax.
Ms Sara Gibb, a Lloyd's Name and administrative secretary of the Gooda
Walker Action Group, said: 'I object to the idea of taxation by stealth. We
are led to believe that because personal tax bands are changed we are going
to be better off. But in fact any gains are offset by huge increases in
indirect taxes.'
Value added tax on fuel remains particularly unpopular. Mr Richard Woodall,
superstore manager at Asda in Norwich, said that the government would be
unwise to make any increase in VAT or any other indirect taxes because of
consumers' nervousness.
Those involved in business were keen to see encouragement for capital
investment. Mr Robin Saxby, chief executive of microchip company Advance
Risc Machines of Cambridge, favoured lower corporation tax and the return of
100 per cent first-year depreciation allowances for capital spending.
Mr Richard Butler, a 44-year-old Tory voter who farms 1,500 acres in
Wiltshire, wanted more generous capital allowances on investment in farm
buildings and machinery.
Mr John Jermine, chairman of Chesterfield mining concern NSM, wanted
increased capital allowances for companies.
But Mr Jermine, who described himself as a high Tory, did not want any cut
in direct taxes. He said: 'I think direct taxes are low enough. We are
competitive with other countries. A lot needs to be done in areas like the
country's infrastructure.'
Others warmed to the theme of cost-saving through greater government
efficiency. Mr Bertie Grotian, a former army officer who runs a marquee
hiring company, said: 'If you look at the Ministry of Defence there must be
one bureaucrat for every soldier. There is plenty of scope for cuts in the
inflated bureaucracies.'
Ms Leisha Fullich, director of education for the London borough of Lewisham,
said: 'I am not saying I favour increases in public spending but something
does need to be done about the environment and education.'
Employers are interested in the chancellor's National Insurance intentions.
Mr Richard Sayer, a Northumberland estate agent who employs eight people,
said: 'Any increase in NI contributions would be crushingly bad.'
Some, including Mr Sayer, would welcome tax cuts.
But Mr Peter Chapman, an unemployed South Shields design engineer and Mr
Alastair Fyfe, duty control manager for European Passenger Services, backed
tax increases if the money were to be used to support key services, notably
the National Health Service. Mr Chapman is a Labour party member, Mr Fyfe a
potential Liberal Democrat voter.
Mr Grotian, who pays himself Pounds 21,000 a year, employs five full-timers
and 10 casuals in the summer, said: 'After taxes and emergency taxes, it is
not worth an unemployed person working. He or she is better off on the
dole.'
Government policy stability was a key concern. Mr Andrew Pimblett, managing
director of crane manufacturer Street Cranes, which employs 150 people,
would like to see manufacturing helped. 'But I do not want anything
short-term. The last thing we need is another boom and bust,' he said.
As an exporter he would prefer interest rates not to change. And Mr Sayer
warned that any rise could give out the wrong messages. He said: 'The
mortgage interest rate isn't so critical as the world thinks. What is far
more critical is the way the public interprets any change.'
Mr Sayer spoke for many in saying mortgage interest tax relief was no longer
a big issue, since its value in real terms had already been whittled down.
Any glimmer of hope focused on reduced duties on beer, wine, spirits and
tobacco to counter cheap cross-Channel imports. Mr Handley at Mansfield
Brewery said he would welcome such a move.
But for Mr Michael Watson, a Newcastle tobacconist, no conceivable reduction
could close the gap of almost 300 per cent between his prices and those of
'smuggled tobacco' sold in local pubs and clubs.
Mr Chapman said: 'What will be needed from this Budget is something to give
people encouragement and hope.' But he isn't holding his breath.
Additional reporting by Alison Maitland, Alan Cane and Charles Batchelor.
</TEXT>
