<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Mazda in pact to make Fiesta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ford is expected to announce this week that it has reached agreement with
Mazda, its Japanese affiliate, for the production in Europe of a Ford car
for sale under the Mazda badge. The two companies have been examining the
possibility of producing a Mazda-badged Ford Fiesta for sale by the Japanese
carmaker in European markets.
The Fiesta is built at three plants in west Europe: Dagenham in the UK,
Cologne in Germany, and Valencia in Spain. Approval of the project could be
announced this week, but a decision on which plant will produce the
Mazda-badged cars may not be made until early next year. Germany is
overwhelmingly Mazda's most important market in Europe. Production of the
Mazda-badged Fiesta is expected to begin in late 1995 or early 1996 with
output of about 30,000 cars a year.
The plan aims to give the loss-making Mazda group its first production
source in Europe, where it has lagged behind Toyota, Nissan, Honda,
Mitsubishi and Suzuki, which all have car plants already in production or
under development in Europe. Mazda, which is 24.5 per cent owned by Ford,
has suffered a steep fall in west European sales of 9.6 per cent in the
first 10 months of this year in a market that has grown by 4.9 per cent.
