<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Faint green light for privatisation: Investors' hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND AND MATTHEW KAMINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For two years Mr Serhii Oksanich was a capitalist in waiting. He and a group
of friends established Kinto, a Kiev investment and securities fund, in the
spring of 1992, but for the first two years there were no securities for
them to trade. 'Our main activity for the past two years has been waiting
for privatisation,' Mr Oksanich said.
The failure of Ukraine's first post-independence government to launch
serious economic reforms, including a mass privatisation programme, meant
months of frustration and false starts for Kinto and the other 400
registered security traders in Ukraine.
Over the past few months, however, things have finally began to change. Over
the summer, 150 large and medium-scale enterprises were privatised using the
certificates granted, with a system of daunting complexity, to each
Ukrainian. In a series of closed tender bids to be closed by the end of this
month, 300 more factories have gone on the block this autumn.
But Ukraine's nascent privatisation is one of eastern Europe's best kept
secrets. In Russia and the Czech Republic, committed governments launched
carefully structured, highly publicised mass privatisation programmes. In
Ukraine the sell-off of factories is happening not with a bang but with a
whimper. It has been not a product of policy at the highest levels but the
quiet result of grassroots enthusiasm.
'They've finally let the genie out of the bottle,' Mr Oksanich said. 'The
process is rotten and they've only let a little bit of privatisation happen,
but now that it's started there's no way to stop it. The only question is
the details and the speed of the process.'
The government of former President Leonid Kravchuk, which authored the
current programme, was at best a luke-warm supporter of privatisation. As a
result, the existing plan is awkward and the bureaucracy has held the
process back.
Western aid officials in Kiev describe the existing programme as 'a
disaster'. 'You cannot speak about meaningful mass participation in the
privatisation process,' says Ms Roberta Feldman, of the International
Financial Corporation, the private sector arm of the World Bank. 'The
programme is complicated and the government did not take a leading role.'
Western officials are optimistic that under the new leadership of President
Leonid Kuchma things will change. They hope that in the new year Ukraine
will begin a public, well-publicised privatisation programme similar to that
of its neighbours.
Businessmen like Mr Oksanich are equally hopeful that, at last, they now
have a government willing to support the development of a market economy
rather than block it. But, like many Ukrainians, who are estimated to obtain
two-thirds of their income outside the official economy, Ukrainian
investment funds are not waiting for the green light from Kiev.
Instead, they have displayed remarkable ingenuity in navigating a multitude
of official road blocks. 'De jure you cannot buy and sell certificates and
foreigners cannot participate in the process,' Mr Oksanich says. 'But de
facto it's easy to get around.' He estimates that about 6m privatisation
certificates have already been invested in Ukraine either in worker buy-outs
or by the investment funds.
A fledgling secondary market in shares in some of these privatised companies
already exists, he says, and he expects about 30 companies to be freely
traded by the end of the year on what he calls 'our baby Nasdaq system'
pioneered a few weeks ago.
Ukraine's subterranean privatisation has already caught the attention of a
few western investment banks active in eastern Europe and Russia. Several
bankers said they were considering setting up operations in Ukraine in the
next few months.
But if privatisation in Ukraine, potentially the largest market in eastern
Europe, has been so devious as to escape the attention of most official
western observers, they are not alone.
Mr Oksanich concedes that for most ordinary Ukrainians 'privatisation
certificates remain largely a myth'.
He says he has avoided paying speeding tickets for the past year by
explaining to policemen how to use their privatisation bank accounts. 'They
tell me they didn't know about this, thank me for the explanation and let me
drive off,' Mr Oksanich says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
