<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Inquiry looms for Berlusconi
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the embattled Italian prime minister, faces a second
turbulent week with an interrogation by Milan magistrates over allegations
of corruption against the backdrop of a threatened general strike on Friday.
He originally had been expected to be questioned by Milan's anti-corruption
magistrates over the weekend; but his lawyer was said to be unwell and the
appointment was put back until this week.
The delay has permitted the prime minister time to ensure greater secrecy
surrounds the encounter, which is likely to take place at a secret location
in Milan.
Mr Berlusconi was angry at the way news of him being under investigation for
corruption while running his Fininvest business empire leaked out last
Tuesday. He is now anxious to protect the full secrecy of the interrogation
and head off the Milan judiciary's tactic of allowing interrogation extracts
to be leaked immediately to the media.
Political analysts have warned that, should any compromising information
emerge, it would be hard for Mr Berlusconi to sustain his policy of refusing
to resign.
Mr Berlusconi insisted all last week he had done no wrong while running
Fininvest, Italy's second largest private business group. He has accused
magistrates of political vendetta.
However, the magistrates' move follows recent admissions by Paolo, his
younger brother, and by Mr Salvatore Sciascia, the head of Fininvest's tax
department, that L330bn (Pounds 132m) was paid between 1989-92 in bribes to
officials of the Guardia di Finanza, the financial police, to ensure
favourable inspections of company books. The Milan magistrates have hinted
they have further evidence up their sleeve. They, too, have admitted in
interviews their credibility is at stake.
It would be surprising if incriminating evidence against Mr Berlusconi was
found but did not leak quickly. But, if the magistrates exercise their
usually astute political judgment, such information would be unlikely to be
made public until after the issue of Friday's general strike is resolved.
This would create too explosive a situation.
</TEXT>
