<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Giscard 'will not run'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing said yesterday that, under current
circumstances, he would not run in next spring's French presidential
election, Reuter reports from Paris.
'To be a candidate, you have to be in a position to be one. And I am not in
that position today,' Mr Giscard d'Estaing, leader of the centre-right UDF
and president from 1974 to 1981, told TF1 television.
Opinion polls show that many right-wing voters who would ideologically be
attracted to him appear to be switching support to Prime Minister Edouard
Balladur, a member of the RPR and a probable contender. Many UDF leaders
have also said they would back Mr Balladur.
Mr Giscard d'Estaing said: 'Something would have to change before February,
either in the opinions of the French people or in developing events, for me
to change my mind.'
</TEXT>
