<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Chechen rebellion defeated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Dzhokhar Dudayev, the president of Chechnya, survived a determined
attempt to overthrow him over the weekend as another burst of fierce
fighting erupted in the Caucasian republic.
United opposition forces launched an assault on Friday evening on Grozny,
the republic's capital, and at one stage even claimed to have seized the
presidential palace. But Mr Dudayev's forces appeared successfully to have
repulsed the attack and claimed they had knocked out 20 opposition tanks.
There were no clear reports of the number of casualties.
Mr Dudayev, a former Soviet air force general, has resisted several attempts
by Moscow-backed rebels to depose him since the Moslem republic of 1m people
declared its independence from Russia three years ago. Yesterday, he accused
Moscow of direct involvement in the latest coup attempt and warned that
hostilities threatened to spread the war beyond the north Caucasus and
'throughout Russia'. Chechen security officials yesterday claimed to have
captured 50 Russian fighters and paraded two of them before the press.
But Russian officials vehemently denied direct participation in Chechnya.
General Vladimir Potapov, chief of staff of the North-Caucasian military
district, said reports suggesting Russian regular servicemen had been been
taken prisoner in Grozny were 'malicious slander'. However, he did not rule
out the possibility that former Russian servicemen could have been hired as
mercenaries.
</TEXT>
