<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / High redundancy offer likely for Halifax and Leeds staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Generous voluntary redundancy terms are likely to be offered to the
27,000-plus staff of Halifax and Leeds Permanent, two of the UK's largest
building societies, as part of the plans for combining the organisations.
Mr Mike Blackburn, Halifax chief executive, will today meet the society's
head-office managers to spell out the agreement to merge and become a public
limited company, the UK's third-largest high street bank with Pounds 90bn in
assets.
Later this week he will meet managers at the Leeds, and meetings with unions
are also planned.
Members of the two societies should receive letters setting out the broad
outline of the agreement within the next two weeks, and a helpline for
customers will operate from today.
The overlap of the two societies' branch networks has already brought
warnings from staff organisations that hundreds of jobs are at risk. While
the societies' managements have not ruled out compulsory redundancies, they
would prefer job losses to be voluntary.
If not, they could face opposition not only from employees but also from
customers who do not want to see a threat to staff in the 1,100 branches or
a cut in the service provided.
The deal must have the approval of 10m investors and borrowers who own the
two societies.
Savings from combining the two networks will be an important part of making
the deal a success.
The societies' boards must avoid announcing such a tough approach to job
losses that the merger falters while ensuring they rationalise the branches
fast enough to prevent a rise in costs.
On average, about 5 per cent of the 22,000 Halifax staff are likely to leave
and be replaced during a year through normal staff turnover, but this
proportion would not be spread evenly either among branches or between the
society's operations.
'There will be short-term reductions in employment,' Mr Blackburn said. 'But
we hope they can be achieved by normal turnover, early retirement and
voluntary redundancies.'
He said the societies wanted to give members as much information as they
could, but it was not known whether they could be told how free shares would
be allocated at flotation before they voted on the merger at special general
meetings in March.
If the societies' merger is approved, it will probably take place in early
summer. The second vote, on whether to float the combined society, is
unlikely until 1996.
