<HEADLINE>
FT  28 NOV 94 / Dole blames UK and France for Nato Bosnia rift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM, LAURA SILBER and BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A leading US politician blamed Britain and France yesterday for a 'complete
breakdown' of the Atlantic alliance and called on the United Nations to
withdraw from Bosnia, where up to 400 peacekeepers were being detained by
the Bosnian Serbs.
Senator Robert Dole, who will lead the Republican majority when the new
Congress meets in January, also called for the lifting of the embargo on
arms supplies to the Bosnian government.
'Get the (UN) soldiers out of the way. Pull 'em out,' Mr Dole said in an
outburst of frustration at European nations which cite the safety of their
troops in Bosnia as an argument against tougher military intervention.
'I think we have a complete breakdown of Nato,' he added, saying that he
held the 'British and French, and primarily the British' responsible.
The senator's remarks reflected indignation over last week's refusal by
European members of Nato to back a US plan to strengthen Bihac, a stronghold
of the Bosnian government, using Nato air power.
In Sarajevo, the UN said Bosnian authorities had accepted its latest
proposal for a ceasefire in Bihac, where the Serbs have almost encircled
government positions and encroached on a 'safe area' notionally protected by
UN resolutions.
UN officials said fighting continued over the weekend on the southern and
south-western outskirts of Bihac. They also reported a large explosion at
the Bosnian army's Bihac headquarters, apparently triggered by the
government forces before they withdrew.
The vulnerability of the UN's 24,000-member force in Bosnia was underlined
yesterday when it emerged that up to 400 peacekeepers were being detained in
Serb-controlled territory.
UN officials said last night they were trying to ascertain the whereabouts
of more than 100 Dutch and 62 British soldiers who appeared to have been
stopped at Serb checkpoints. About 250 peacekeepers were detained last week
after Nato launched air strikes on Serb positions in Croatia and Bosnia.
Mr Jovan Zametica, a senior Bosnian Serb official, described the incidents
as an 'unfortunate misunderstanding' and hinted that the peacekeeping troops
might be handed back their freedom of movement.
Mr William Perry, the US defence secretary, yesterday conceded that the
Serbs had, in effect, won the war in Bosnia. In remarks that reflected
European concerns and differed sharply from Senator Dole, he said lifting
the arms embargo could stoke the war, and expressed doubt over a military
solution in Bosnia.
Amid growing signs of disarray over Bosnian policy in the main western
capitals, Mr Andrei Kozyrev, Russia's foreign minister, said he had
'successful and very useful' talks in Belgrade with Serbian president
Slobodan Milosevic. He said Mr Milosevic was working for a ceasefire in
Bihac and throughout Bosnia.
Mr Perry said he was not prepared to recommend the deployment of the
hundreds of thousands of US troops necessary to reverse the tide of the war.
He said he sent 2,000 US Marines to the Adriatic on Friday 'for contingency
purposes'. Heargued that Nato had done whatever it had been asked to do, and
blamed the UN for the absence of more vigorous action.
US and Russia square off over security, Page 2
