<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Nato jets in action as Serbs give Bihac ultimatum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serb forces closing in on the town of Bihac last night gave its
defenders a 24-hour-ultimatum to surrender as Nato aircraft were ordered
into action but apparently failed to make any strikes.
Within hours of the Nato action, it was disclosed in Washington that 2,000
US marines had been ordered to the Adriatic as a possible support for United
Nations forces.
The ultimatum to the mainly Moslem government forces holed up in Bihac came
from General Manojlo Milovanovic, the Bosnian Serbs' chief of staff, who
said the defenders must put down their arms by this evening. 'If they do no
not surrender, I cannot guarantee that their lives will be spared, because
they have committed crimes against the Serbs,' he said in a grim-voiced
message.
The United Nations said it called on Nato aircraft to over-fly the area
because of a danger to civilians and UN personnel. But the bombers, which
were fired on by SAM-6 missiles, did not make any strikes because they
failed to locate any targets, a UN official said.
The Bosnian Serbs claimed two Nato bombs had landed and said Bosnian
government positions would suffer 'the least peaceful of nights' as a
result. Serb-controlled media said the Serb forces and their allies in a
renegade Moslem force led by Mr Fikret Abdic were advancing on the town
centre. A radio station controlled by Mr Abdic said 400 of his men had
entered the town.
UN officials said the Serbs were about a mile from Bosnian army headquarters
but could not confirm that there had been any change of position yesterday.
In Washington, Pentagon officials described the despatch of the marines as
'strictly precautionary', adding that the amphibious group would be
available if needed to support UN forces in Bosnia. The marines, on an
amphibious flotilla headed by the USS Nassau, were ordered to cut short
their visit to the French port of Toulon and sail to the Adriatic.
Although the Nato allies have begun discussions of a possible US role in
providing cover if Unprofor should have to withdraw from Bosnia, officials
in Washington said no detailed contingency plan for withdrawal had been
agreed.
President Bill Clinton has insisted that there would be no question of
sending US ground troops to Bosnia except within the framework of a peace
deal agreed by all sides.
The Serb threats followed the announcement by the UN of a ceasefire in the
Bihac area, and a day of arguments between the UN and the Bosnian government
as to how badly it was being violated and by whom.
UN and Nato struggle, Page 2
</TEXT>
