<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow stages recovery in low
volume
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices reversed the declining course seen earlier in the week to
close yesterday's half-day session solidly higher in extremely light volume,
writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 33.64 at 3,708.27. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 rose 2.36 at 452.29, while the
American Stock Exchange composite gained 2.25 at 434.65. The Nasdaq
composite was up 5.82 at 742.52. Trading volume on the NYSE came to 109m
shares.
Program trading early in the morning helped to push the market to a positive
close for the first time since November 16.
The market closed at 1 pm for the Thanksgiving holiday, after being shut on
Thursday.
US Treasury prices also reversed their previous course, holding steady after
a week of relatively steady gains. Two-year notes were flat, while the
benchmark 30-year Treasuries gained slightly.
Several cyclical stocks rebounded from losses earlier in the week. Aluminum
Company of America rose Dollars 2 3/8 at Dollars 80 3/8 , Allied Signal
gained Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 32 1/8 , Caterpillar was up Dollars  3/4 at
Dollars 53 3/8 , United Technologies climbed Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 56 1/2
and International Paper increased Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 69 5/8 .
Both Bankers Trust and Gibson Greeting gained on news that the two had
settled a lawsuit filed by Gibson over derivative losses.
Bankers Trust rose Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 57 1/8 and Gibson was up Dollars
1 1/8 at Dollars 13 7/8 after the companies announced an out-of-court
settlement that essentially released Gibson from Dollars 14m that it owed
the bank from two swap agreements.
The settlement put an end to the smaller of two derivatives-related suits
filed against Bankers Trust.
American Depository Re-ceipts of Sony, which are traded on the New York
Stock Exchange, rose Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 51 3/4 after Mr Akio Morita,
the chairman, announced his retirement. Sony was the first Japanese company
to have a listing on the NYSE. News that Archer-Daniels-Midland planned a
Dollars 700m expansion of an Iowa plant did not help the agribusiness giant.
Its shares fell Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 28 1/2 .
Brazil
Stock prices closed 3.8 per cent lower in thin Sao Paulo trading, dragged
down by tight liquidity, concern about small banks, and anxiety about how
President-elect Fernando Henrique Cardoso will form his cabinet.
The Bovespa index of the 55 most-active shares ended off 1,747 at 43,987.
Analysts said that stocks were depressed - the Bovespa index has dropped 8.3
per cent this month - as major domestic and foreign players were mostly out
of the market.
Venezuela
Caracas plunged across the board to a four-month low, led by panic selling
of the benchmark stock, Electricidad de Caracas. The Merinvest composite
index closed 2.85, or 2.4 per cent lower at 117.24, down nearly 20 per cent
this month.
Electricidad de Caracas tumbled 12.00 bolivars to 199.00 bolivars, down 40
per cent since October 28, as investors offloaded existing shares to
participate in a one-for-six rights issue.
</TEXT>
