<DATE>941126
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money: A legal way to rig the market - Serious Money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR, personal finance editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What is the difference between a gumshoe and a greenshoe? And which would
you send to track down the other?
Lovers of classic American detective fiction will have no trouble with
gumshoe - the sleuth for hire. Greenshoe has been slower to cross the
Atlantic, even as a practice. But it is a term new-issue fans would do well
to grapple with - for it is an integral part of what old-fashioned investors
might describe as authorised market-rigging.
When a big international issue - such as BT, TeleWest or BSkyB - comes to
the stock market, everybody connected with it is very keen that the market
price should stay above the issue price for a decent period after the
launch. The professional investors do not want to lose money. The company
does not want to end up with a lot of disgruntled shareholders. And the
banks underwriting the issue want to keep both clients and large investors
sweet.
So, the banks have found a natty little mechanism which allows them
effectively to guarantee that the share price will not fall below the issue
price for a month. The mechanism is simplicity itself.
If the market price gets dangerously close to the issue price - because
there are more sellers than buyers - the underwriters just buy up the excess
shares. And this altruism costs them nothing.
Here is how it works. Underwriters are wholesalers: they buy shares from the
issuer and sell them on to investors. Normally, they aim to match the number
of shares they buy from the issuer with the number of shares they sell to
investors. But if the underwriters are planning a price support operation,
they deliberately sell more shares to investors than they buy from the
issuer and leave themselves short of stock.
Being short of stock is dangerous: if the price goes up, you could have to
pay more to buy in shares than you got when you sold them. So, the
underwriters need an insurance policy which guarantees them against such
losses.
This is where the greenshoe comes in. It is an option granted by the issuer
to the underwriters which allows them to buy additional shares in the
company at the offer price if they need to cover their short sales.
Like any insurance policy, the greenshoe is an enabling tool, not an
objective. The point of the exercise is to enable the underwriters to
support the share price if necessary.
If the price is looking soggy, the underwriters do not exercise their option
to purchase shares from the issuers; instead, they buy the extra shares they
need to cover their short sales through the stock market. And, in squaring
their own books, they coincidentally support the share price of a valued
client at a delicate moment. It is an exercise of great beauty.
Everybody who matters knows exactly what is going on. The prospectus will
have a little clause saying something like: 'The underwriters may over-allot
or effect transactions which stabilise or maintain the market price of the
shares at levels above those which might otherwise prevail in the open
market.'
The over-allotment option is limited to 15 per cent of the shares being sold
and there is a 30-day limit to the support operation. And when the
underwriters have stopped supporting the price, they put out an announcement
saying so. Meanwhile, any professional investor worried about the short-term
outlook has taken the opportunity to sell some shares at the issue price.
Fine, but . . .
The guy left out in the cold is - as so often - the private investor. Say
you have bought shares in TeleWest or BSkyB and notice the share price
hovering close to the issue price for several weeks after the launch; you
could well shrug your shoulders and hope that floor will hold. It might -
but there is no guarantee once the artificial prop has been removed.
It is, normally, illegal for companies to buy their own shares. And illegal,
covert share price-rigging was the nub of the Guinness scandal. Greenshoes
are legal, open and above board. But market-rigging is market-rigging even
when it has its acceptable face on.
The British Assets' reorganisation looks like a fudge. The basic problem is
that, in order to get an above-average yield on their investment portfolio,
the managers have invested in securities unlikely to produce adequate
capital growth.
The honest answer to this might be to cut the dividend. Instead, they are
proposing a pseudo split-capital trust which leaves shareholders with
Hobson's choice. Either they cling on to all their income - and watch their
capital growth being diluted by other investors' warrants - or they accept
an immediate reduction in yield.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Assets Trust.
</CO>
<XX>
